 <img src="http://liquid2k.com/darkreaver/images/booicon2.gif" BORDER=0> </p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#aaaaaa><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub25.ezboard.com/uartistdave.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Artist Dave</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Karbonite</span><br> <font color=#336699>(4/1/02 3:05:03 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub25.ezboard.com/fpolykarbonbbsfrm23.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=5294.topic&index=3>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.boomspeed.com/artist_dave/daveicon.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Comicpages - POK!</span><hr size=1> There's nothing at all wrong with the art; I think it's great; very professional-looking.  I think the problems are in the panel layout.  Here's my breakdown of the pages:<br>
<br>
Page 5:<br>
<br>
-The panels containing the close-up's of the character's eyes seem like they're floating in the middle of the page.  Because they're so small, they don't give the depth or scope of the character's face.  Try adjoining the two panels, making it one divided box, and attaching it to the side of the left-most panel.<br>
-To give a better idea of the surroundings, try adding a silhouette of the character in the middle of the field.  I think you should also give more room to the drawing of the fields.<br>
-Last panel: something doesn't look right about it.  It may have to do with his expression.  One idea for expand on is that he's sweaty, tired and probably bored, and he's just looking around and taking a break, when lo! and behold, he sees the column of smoke.  <br>
<br>
Page 6:<br>
<br>
-First panel:  It looks too bland.  Try adding the character's silhouette staring up at the column of smoke.  Make the landscape look more like a wheat field than a block of white space.  Every panel has to convey a crucial part of the story.<br>
-2nd panel:  Good expression.  However, since he's looking upwards in the previous page, I think he should be looking in the same direction here.<br>
-the two smaller panels could be larger.  Otherwise, this is good.<br>
<br>
Page 7:<br>
<br>
-1st panel:  What would look really good is if you put the character himself into the panel, showing him running frantically towards the distant village.  Speed lines would work very nicely here.<br>
-2nd and 3rd panels are good, but try to give the impression that the main character is looking on at the atrocities, like an over-the-shoulder camera angle.<br>
-One thing you could try in order to convey the &quot;hero's&quot; emotions at this time is, make the three panels shorter, and try to squeeze in a CCU of the hero's eyes, perhaps in anger or rage.<br>
<br>
Page 8:<br>
-Very nice action shot.  Unfortunately, it takes up almost the entire page, leaving little room for the punch itself.<br>
-2nd panel:  The poses look awkward; they don't look like the result of a right cross.  The *pok* sound looks like the bad guy's sound when he's landing.  *pok* also isn't a very powerful sound for a punch...try &quot;crunch&quot;, &quot;wham&quot;, or something less traditional.<br>
<br>
I think page 8 can be redone.  The rising action and climax (for the page itself) don't work very well.  You want the punch to be climactic, like the main part of the page.  What I would do is perhaps for a small-ish upper panel, showing the &quot;executioner&quot; glancing to the side from his handiwork, and then the &quot;hero&quot; appears out of nowhere.  For the &quot;punch&quot; panel, use the one you have showing him about to punch the bad guy, except draw the scene so that the punch connects, and the bad guy's face thrown to the side from the sheer force of it.<br>
<br>
By no means am I an experienced comic book artist myself, so take my advice however you want.  Hope it helps! <p>--Mad, adj: Affected with a high degree of intellectual independence. 
