<br>
Ryo Ohki: Hopefully the smoke will look like smoke once I do it in double size with a brush, and not half size with a pencil. I'll try to make the small panels a bit larger. I'll also see if I can figure out a way of making the characters shock seem a bit more natural.... hmmm.... I'll have to think about this one.... well....thanks anyhow...<br>
<br>
Darkreaver66: Thanks for the kind words. The twisting of the bad guys body is a very good point. I'll draw it in there, somehow, someway.<br>
I don't think I'll do a close-up of the beheading, though. I want it distant, sort of to illustrate the good-guys inability to do anything about it. I'll try to find some way of centering the readers eye on it. Anyhow, if it is violent close-ups you want, then you'll get plenty of that later in the story.<br>
<br>
Artist Dave: Thanks very much for the kind words and for taking the time to break down every single panel. The art is going to get much, much better before the comic is finished(These drawings are still what I consider to be layouts).<br>
ok... now...<br>
Page5:<br>
- Yup, I'll have to do something with the eye close-ups.<br>
-  I will not, however, need more shots of the field. Remember this is page 5..... guess what I've used the previous 4 pages for?????? (OK, it's not all fields, but pretty much).<br>
- Yup, the last panel will have to go. I'll try to get a better angle on it and put more care into his expression.<br>
Page6:<br>
- The first panel is a build up to the next page. The reason it's a totally straight line for the wheat field is that I forgot to draw it in on paper(I'm working on bluelines from the original thumbnail layouts), and just quickly  added the line in photoshop. Hopefully the picture will be more interesting once it's finished, with nice things like the sun shining through the smoke(That's not gonna be easy to draw), and the long shadows. Don't think there will be no silhuette, but maybe there will be some &quot;shock&quot;-lines around the fire.<br>
- No, he shouldn't be looking upwards. First he looks up at the smoke in the sky, then he looks down to the fire. Simple as that.<br>
- Yes, the small panels will be larger.<br>
Page7:<br>
There will be no &quot;over-the-shoulder&quot; camera. I like the idea of presenting this scene from a first-person view, and I'm gonna stick to it. But, yes, there will be speed-lines. Quite alot of them, I think.<br>
I will see if there is room for some shots of the good-guys eyes, but I seriously doubt it's enough space for it(Although it would make a nice parallel too some of the earlier pages). <br>
Page8:<br>
I don't think the &quot;climax&quot; should always have the largest space. This is also a question of the readers eye-movement. Hopefully it will work better when you have to turn the page(Not just look at the screen), since the natural position the readers eyes sees first when he\she turns a page is the middle section of the second page(This happens almost always). If the punch itself was placed there, it would ruin the climax somewhat(Since the climax would be seen first).<br>
Hopefully, by letting the build-up panel be seen first, the reader will more carefully examine the running sequence(To find out why he's so mad), and the punch will not loose it's power.<br>
That's the general idea, at least.<br>
However, I will see if I can make it work better, somehow...<br>
(But I really like the page, so I'm not sure)<br>
POK! may not be the best sound effect, no....<br>
But, anyhow.... thanks alot for all the comments, it was really helpfull.<br>
